1. According to the data of 100 randomly selected teachers, calculate the total number of teachers using software C or E: a+b=100-10-15-30=45;
2. Calculate the frequency of using software C or E in the sample: 45/100;
3. Estimate the probability by frequency, and calculate the estimated number of teachers using software C or E among 300 teachers in the school: 300×(45/100).

1. Calculate the frequency of using software D in the sample as the probability of using D in a single draw: p=30/100=3/10;
2. Determine that in 3 independent repeated trials, the number X of teachers using D is at least 2, that is, X=2 or X=3;
3. According to the binomial distribution probability formula, calculate P(X=2)=C₃²×(3/10)²×(7/10) and P(X=3)=C₃³×(3/10)³;
4. Sum the results to get the required probability: P=P(X=2)+P(X=3).

